rations of the conceptualizing of religion in the fields of 'anthropology', 'community', 'family', 'institution', 'law', 'media', and 'politics' among others. The second section is dedicated to case studies of 'religious practices' from the perspective of their actors. The third section presents major theoretical discourses that explore the globally significant diversity and multiplicity of religion. Altogether, sixty-one authors from different parts of the world encourage a rethinking of religious practice in an expanded, transcultural, globalized, and postcolonial world.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aTheology, PracticalvHandbooks, manuals, etc. 4aGlobalisierung. 4aInterkulturalität. 4aReligion. 4aRitual. 7aRELIGION / Christian Ministry / Pastoral Resources.2bisacsh  aInterculturality.  aglobalization.  areligion.  aritual practice.1 aAbdallah, Mahmoud, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAdam, Júlio César, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAfdal, Geir Sigmund, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAsamoah-Gyadu, J. Kwabena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAuga, Ulrike E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnard, Marcel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeyers, Jaco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCilliers, Johan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClasquin-Johnson, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabul